# TypeScript Standards

`strict` is on. Keep it green — no `// @ts-ignore` without a justifying comment.

## Naming

- Files: components/types → PascalCase (`Certificate.ts`, `Button.tsx`); services/hooks/utils → camelCase (`certificatesService.ts`, `formatDate.ts`).
- `type` over `interface` for models/props (matches existing code). `PascalCase` types, `camelCase` values, `UPPER_SNAKE` constants.

## Typing

- Type all exported function params and return values. Don't leak `any` across boundaries.
- When mapping untrusted external data (Firestore docs, API JSON), narrow explicitly and use `satisfies` to verify the shape:

```ts
return {
  id: d.id,
  name: String(data.name ?? ''),
  expiryDate: normalizeToISODate(data.expiryDate),
} satisfies Certificate;
```

- Use `Pick`/`Partial`/`Omit` to derive input types from domain models instead of redefining them.
- Prefer `as const` for literal config objects (keys, palettes, theme scales).

## Practices

- No unused exports/vars. Avoid default exports except Expo Router route files.
- Don't narrate code with comments; comment only non-obvious intent, edge cases, or platform quirks (as the existing services do).
- Handle async errors deliberately — swallow only with a `console.warn` and a reason (e.g. best-effort storage cleanup), never an empty `catch {}` silently.
